    <section id="living-with" class="content-section">
      <h2>Living with stomatitis</h2>
      <p>Stomatitis causes chronic, severe pain. Cats with it often can't eat comfortably, drop food, drool, or avoid eating altogether. It is frequently dismissed as routine dental disease — or treated with periodic antibiotics and pain medication that manage symptoms without addressing the cause. The result is a cat who is in pain most of the time, in a way that isn't always obvious to the people around them.</p>
      <p>Yams had stomatitis alongside CKD, dehydration, and hypertension. Treating the mouth pain was complicated by his kidney disease limiting some medication options. Stomatitis in a multi-condition cat is genuinely hard to manage — the interactions between conditions constrain what you can do, and there often isn't a clean answer. What there is: a conversation worth having specifically and explicitly about pain management, not just about managing the diagnosis.</p>
      <div class="content-callout content-callout--urgent">
        <strong>Stomatitis is painful.</strong> If your cat is showing signs of mouth discomfort, don't let it wait for the next routine appointment. Chronic pain affects every aspect of daily life — eating, grooming, behaviour, engagement. It deserves urgent attention.
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="advocacy" class="content-section">
      <h2>What good advocacy looks like</h2>
      <ul class="vet-questions">
        <li><strong>Ask whether this is stomatitis or routine periodontal disease — and how they're distinguishing them.</strong> They look similar and have different treatment paths. The distinction matters.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask specifically about pain level and pain management.</strong> Not just "we'll manage the inflammation" — but what is being done right now, today, for the pain? Stomatitis pain is severe enough to warrant an explicit answer.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask about full mouth extraction as an option.</strong> It sounds extreme. For many cats with stomatitis it is transformative, and it has the highest long-term success rate of any treatment. If it hasn't been raised, ask why and what the alternative trajectory looks like.</li>
        <li><strong>If your cat has CKD or other conditions, ask specifically how those constrain medication options.</strong> Some treatments routinely used for stomatitis carry kidney risks. You need your vet to address this intersection directly.</li>
        <li><strong>Ask how you'll know if treatment is working.</strong> What are the signs of improvement? What's the timeline? If there's no measurable goal, there's no way to know when to change course.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

